## Notes

- This lane keeps full Gemini extension packaging and a production-ready 9-hook Go runtime: `SessionStart`, `SessionEnd`, `BeforeModel`, `AfterModel`, `BeforeToolSelection`, `BeforeAgent`, `AfterAgent`, `BeforeTool`, and `AfterTool`.
- For the generated Go starter, `gemini.*Continue()` helpers mean a true no-op Gemini hook response. Use `gemini.BeforeToolAllow()` or `gemini.AfterToolAllow()` only when you explicitly want `"decision":"allow"` in the emitted JSON.
- Gemini treats `SessionStart` and `SessionEnd` as advisory hooks, so `continue`, `decision`, `reason`, and `stopReason` are ignored there. Prefer `SessionStartAddContext(...)` and `systemMessage` for lifecycle behavior.
- Use `gemini.SessionStartMessage(...)` and `gemini.SessionEndMessage(...)` when you want a typed helper for advisory `systemMessage` output.
- Use `gemini.BeforeModelOverrideRequestValue(...)` to rewrite `llm_request`, `gemini.BeforeModelSyntheticResponseValue(...)` to short-circuit a model call with a synthetic response, and `gemini.AfterModelReplaceResponseValue(...)` to rewrite returned `llm_response` objects from normal Go maps or structs.
- Use `gemini.BeforeToolSelectionConfig(...)` when you want to steer official Gemini tool selection with `toolConfig.mode`. Gemini currently accepts `allowedFunctionNames` only together with `mode: "ANY"`. Use `gemini.BeforeToolSelectionDisableAll()` when you intentionally want `mode: "NONE"`.
- Use `gemini.BeforeToolSelectionAllowOnly(...)` when you want an allowlist in the vendor-accepted `ANY` shape, `gemini.BeforeToolSelectionForceAny(...)` when you want Gemini to call at least one tool, `gemini.BeforeToolSelectionForceAuto()` when you want explicit `AUTO` mode, and `gemini.BeforeToolSelectionQuiet()` when you only want to suppress hook metadata for the tool-selection step.
- Use `gemini.BeforeAgentAddContext(...)` for turn-local prompt context, `gemini.BeforeAgentDeny(...)` to discard a prompt, `gemini.AfterAgentDeny(...)` to force a retry, and `gemini.AfterAgentClearContext()` when you intentionally want Gemini to clear prior conversation memory.
- Use `gemini.BeforeAgentStop(...)` when you want to stop the turn but keep the prompt in history, `gemini.AfterAgentStop(...)` when you want to stop the session without retrying, and `gemini.AfterModelStop(...)`, `gemini.BeforeToolStop(...)`, or `gemini.AfterToolStop(...)` when you intentionally want `continue:false` loop-stop behavior.
- Use `gemini.BeforeToolRewriteInputValue(...)` when you want to rewrite `tool_input` from a normal Go map or struct.
- Use `gemini.AfterToolAddContext(...)` to append extra text to the tool result, or `gemini.AfterToolTailCallValue(...)` to request an immediate follow-up tool call with typed Go args.
- `plugin-kit-ai test` and `plugin-kit-ai dev` stay focused on the stable Claude/Codex runtime fixture lanes. For Gemini, use `go test ./...`, `plugin-kit-ai generate --check .`, `plugin-kit-ai validate . --platform gemini --strict`, `plugin-kit-ai inspect . --target gemini`, `plugin-kit-ai capabilities --mode runtime --platform gemini`, then exercise the extension through `gemini extensions link .` and a real Gemini CLI session.
- Use `make test-gemini-runtime` for the deterministic repo-local Gemini runtime gate before you bother with a real CLI session.
- Use `make test-gemini-runtime-live` when you need the dedicated opt-in real CLI runtime smoke.
- Keep Gemini-specific authored assets inside `plugin/targets/gemini/...`.
- Keep stdout reserved for Gemini hook JSON responses and write diagnostics to stderr only.
